   <mods:abstract>The Spinozan theory of belief fixation is the result of some remarks made by Baruch Spinoza about the nature of the mind in The Ethics. Modern scientific methods applied to human minds have yielded evidence supporting Spinoza's insights. In this dissertation, I explore some of the implications of the Spinozan theory of belief fixation. Insights from the Spinozan theory of belief fixation are applied to topics in epistemology, metaethics, meta normativity, and the nature of propaganda. Two appendices appear at the end. The first appendix provides a survey of the evidence supporting the Spinozan theory of belief fixation. The second appendix provides additional support for the claims made in chapter 2. The Spinozan theory of belief fixation is an interesting and provocative account of our cognitive architecture. Those who are interested in the Spinozan theory of belief fixation will find themselves with an embarrassment of riches when considering which of its myriad philosophical implications to explore.</mods:abstract>
